ntity** on that `i32`; on wasm they resolve to the `CharCodeId` intrinsic (no-op).\nPer ADR 0026, `Wasm.*` is first-order only — no HOFs, no `Prelude`. All types are `Prim`\n(`Char` / `Int`).\n\nThe accompanying `Wasm/Char.js` provides them for stock `purs` / `purs-backend-es` (there a\n`Char` is a JS UTF-16 unit, so the JS impls use `charCodeAt` / `fromCharCode`).\n","declarations":[{"children":[],"comments":"The `Char`'s Unicode code point. On wasm: the `CharCodeId` intrinsic (identity).\n","info":{"declType":"value","type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Function"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Char"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Int"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"kind":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[16,42],"name":"/tmp/xNgt2G/purescript-wasm-base-v0.1.1/src/Wasm/Char.purs","start":[16,1]},"title":"toCodePoint"},{"children":[],"comments":"The `Char` for a code point, **unchecked** (the caller guarantees a valid code point; the\nUTF-8 decoder only ever produces valid ones). On wasm: the `CharCodeId` intrinsic (identity).\n","info":{"declType":"value","type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Function"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Int"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Char"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"kind":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[20,44],"name":"/tmp/xNgt2G/purescript-wasm-base-v0.1.1/src/Wasm/Char.purs","start":[20,1]},"title":"fromCodePoint"}],"name":"Wasm.Char","reExports":[]},{"comments":"WasmBase `Wasm.Int` (ADR 0026/0028): first-order `Int` primitives, so WasmBase modules —\nand ulib shadows of *low-level* prelude modules (e.g. `Data.Functor`, which imports no\narithmetic) — can run without `Prelude` (which would be circular). Types a